The paper proposes a deep neural network architecture for learning fixed-length vector representations of audio segments excised from a speech corpus. This involves natural language processing and speech recognition, which are both subfields of computer science. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). 

The paper also involves the use of skipgrams and continuous bag-of-words for training, which are techniques used in natural language processing and machine learning. This makes cs.SD (Sound) and cs.SI (Speech and Audio Processing) likely sub-categories as well. 

The paper also evaluates and analyzes the learned word embeddings on word similarity benchmarks, which involves machine learning and data analysis. This makes cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category. 

Finally, the paper does not involve any specific hardware or system architecture, so sub-categories such as cs.AR (Hardware Architecture) or cs.OS (Operating Systems) are unlikely.
